    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1939-06-15T09:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1939-06-15T09:00:00-05:00" n="727"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d727">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.51/6919: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in France</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Wilson</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Paris</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1939-06-15T15:00:00+01:00"
                            >June 15, 1939—3 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received June 15—11:12 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1135. Embassy’s 1061, June 3, 3 p.m.; and 1107, June 10, 1 p.m.<note n="67"
                        xml:id="d727fn67">Latter not printed.</note> Chauvel tells me that the
                    Foreign Office has received a letter from the Ministry of Colonies to the effect
                    that in view of the interest of the United States in these tung oil shipments it
                    has been decided to exempt the shipments from payment of the Indo-China transit
                    duty and to <pb facs="0761" n="757" xml:id="pg_757"/> provide the necessary
                    railway facilities so that the total amount of the shipments may be effected
                    before the end of the year.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Wilson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
